Management_Condition_Comments: Main ditch gone on N and W sides. Visitor erosion of paths where cross rampart, with horse and quad bikes. Vegetation re-growth. Some quarrying.
Management_Land_Use_Comments: Mixed woodland since 19th century with internal tracks. Bracken, bramble, sapling and coppice re-growth. Some quarrying.

Management_Condition_Comments: Natural and animal erosion with sheep scrapes. General improvement as part of management agreements. Public Right of Way and permissive paths. Past tree removal is causing erosion around the stumps. Site now under management agreements.
Management_Land_Use_Comments: Potatoes once grown on the site, but vegetation now managed.

Management_Condition_Comments: Although the circuit continuous in part, the site is generally damaged and tree covered. An ancient landslip seems to have taken the defences on the E and S. An access track runs NE to SW passing through the NW entrance.
Management_Land_Use_Comments: A wooded private site with access problems.

Management_Condition_Comments: Slumping has occurred around the SE corner. Rabbit problem. However, there has been some general improvement with scrub control measures.
Management_Land_Use_Comments: The interior is arable and pasture at present. Wooded ramparts. There is a history of ploughing generally.

Management_Condition_Comments: Visitor numbers great, but erosion repair has taken place. Scrub especially on the W side could be a problem. Rabbit control measures. Otherwise condition generally good.
Management_Land_Use_Comments: Upland pasture, moorland and scrub. Medieval ringwork.

Management_Condition_Comments: Survives only as a cropmark. Possible further earthworks may exist in woodland to the W.
Management_Land_Use_Comments: The site has been ploughed for centuries.

Management_Condition_Comments: Some tree planting and recreation effects. Pheasant rearing on site with farm landscaping to E.
Management_Land_Use_Comments: Wooded on the W half of the site with pasture on the E half. Mature trees with general rough grazing and some tree planting. Past remains of post-medieval stone cottage.

Management_Condition_Comments: Animal disturbance, particularly around the S rampart. Tree clearance has taken place. Two public footpaths close-by. Despite regular ploughing, with probable deterioration of archaeological layers, site generally  stable and little has changed over the past 25 years.
Management_Land_Use_Comments: Interior has been regularly ploughed. FC conifer plantation on W ramparts, which are vulnerable.

Management_Condition_Comments: Wooded with windthrow problems as mature trees growing on the rampart. Public footpath through the middle of the site.
Management_Land_Use_Comments: Oak, ash, cherry and yew trees on site.

Management_Condition_Comments: Private and damaged site precludes further comment.
Management_Land_Use_Comments: Tree covered with conifer plantation and broadleaved woodland.

Management_Condition_Comments: SW corner totally destroyed by quarrying and extensive linear quarries in the interior. Recreation pressures now being addressed. Animal damage. Many paths.
Management_Land_Use_Comments: Site initially planted with tree in the 1960's. Heavily wooded, but in 2008/2009 whole of N half of the site clear felled. Woodland management by the Woodland Trust continues. Part pasture in the interior. Quarries.

Management_Condition_Comments: Good condition, with management by the National Trust. Recreation pressure generally managed despite no full management plan and wind-throw of scattered trees could be a problem. Repair and re-routing of access path through W entrance.
Management_Land_Use_Comments: Bracken can be a problem for interpretation during the summer and control carried out.

Management_Condition_Comments: Wooded with beech wind-throw problems as a result of mature beech trees, some removed in 2007-2008. Generally improving in condition.
Management_Land_Use_Comments: Heavily wooded ramparts, but now the subject of a substantial management plan and agreement. Sapling, scrub and brambles managed. Interior part wood part pasture.

Management_Condition_Comments: Little is known about the site, but damaged.
Forestry clearance has damaged the site which is generally at risk. On Heritage at Risk Register (2015).
Management_Land_Use_Comments: Dense conifers over most of site, with grassed areas of forest track and open wood at the edge if a pasture field. Scrub on ramparts and mature trees in the ditch.Little visible.

Management_Condition_Comments: Site relatively stable, but scrub and wind-throw problems remain.
Badly affected by agriculture and development, the latter especially on the W and S.
Management_Land_Use_Comments: Mostly under pasture. Scrub and wood on N and S slopes.

Management_Condition_Comments: Badly damaged by road and agriculture. Intensive ploughing for many years has eroded the ramparts and nearly obliterated the site. Archaeological deposits probably truncated.
Management_Land_Use_Comments: A4137 main Hereford road bisects the site.

Management_Condition_Comments: The site is almost destroyed with only vestigal remains extant.
Management_Land_Use_Comments: Generally grazed pasture, but near destruction.

Management_Condition_Comments: Wooded overgrown site within an area of managed woodland of Haffield Park, but generally improving in condition. There have been issues relating to harvesting and management in the past. There are public footpaths nearby.
Despite modern buildings of Camp Farm in the interior, wooded ramparts and former quarrying, it is still an impressive site. Permissive path.
Management_Land_Use_Comments: Interior devoted to Camp Farm and agriculture. Quarrying.

Management_Condition_Comments: Conifer plantation in interior now clear felled. Grazing by deer has improved the site. Site ploughed during WWII.
Management_Land_Use_Comments: Woodland is now actively managed by owners.

Management_Condition_Comments: Forestry Commission plantation cleared in 2011, the site now managed with scrub clearance once a year. Generally improving situation.
Management_Land_Use_Comments: Sited within a Forestry Commission plantation with free public access. Now pasture.

Management_Condition_Comments: General deterioration until management since 2010. Erosion especially on the N rampart. S part of Hollybush Hill to S quarried away.
Management_Land_Use_Comments: Heavily overgrown and wooded in part; open, very rough grazing and bare rock to N. SSSI.

Management_Condition_Comments: In poor condition and badly affected by ploughing over centuries.
Management_Land_Use_Comments: Part wooded, but most under arable.

Main_Display_Name: Pen-Twyn Camp, Brilley, Herefordshire (Pen Twyn Camp)
Management_Condition_Comments: Defences much damaged, especially on S where absent and now a hedge line. Thought to be little change since the 1980's and that the site is stable in condition.
Management_Land_Use_Comments: Part conifer plantation and pasture. Access problems.

Management_Condition_Comments: Continuous ploughing has mostly destroyed the site to a cropmark, but part still visible.
Management_Land_Use_Comments: Formerly arable, now part of Higher Level Stewardship Scheme under pasture and stable as a result.

Main_Display_Name: Poston Camp, Herefordshire (Lower Park Wood Camp)
Management_Condition_Comments: Management in 1980's has halted deterioration. W end of main rampart, scarp slope and berm lie in woodland. Rest of rampart has scattered beech trees capable of windthrow. Some animal erosion.
Management_Land_Use_Comments: W end of main rampart, scarp slope and berm lie in woodland. Otherwise pasture.

Management_Condition_Comments: Timber operations have damaged the site and generally in poor condition, with loss of ramparts in part around the circuit.
Management_Land_Use_Comments: Wooded with mixed oak, ash and beech.

Management_Condition_Comments: In fairly good condition despite the trees. Now part of management agreements which should assist in the preservation of the site and alleviate problems.
Management_Land_Use_Comments: Wooded ramparts. The interior is part orchard and has been so for many years.

Management_Condition_Comments: A quarter of the W part of the interior destroyed by quarrying, beginning in 1935 to a depth of 6m and then used as a toxic waste dump, finishing in the 1980's. The ramparts are eroded and the site is continuing to deteriorate. On Heritage at Risk Register (2015).
Management_Land_Use_Comments: About 25% of the W part of the site has been used as a quarry and toxic waste dump. The remaining 75% is down to pasture.

Management_Condition_Comments: Despite the wooded and damaged nature of the site, much can be ascertained. A private track runs through the site from N to S. No management at present.
Management_Land_Use_Comments: Deciduous woodland (oak, ask with some sweet chestnut planting in the interior) with dense bramble.

Main_Display_Name: Wall Hills Camp, Ledbury, Herefordshire (Wall Hills, Ledbury)
Management_Condition_Comments: Affected by development and trees on ramparts. Conservation issues continue with access problems. Management agreements in the 1980's and 1990's resulted in tree thinning and coppicing of rampart trees. Damage to the site, including dumping, trackwork and grading resulted in repairs completed in 2011. The outer bank is fragmentary and ditch filled in. Deep ploughed during WWII, but it appears that ploughing ceased in the 1970's.
Management_Land_Use_Comments: General arable and pasture. Some wood on ramparts.

Management_Condition_Comments: General decline in condition due to animal erosion, scrub (on nearly three-quarters of the rampart) and cultivation. Area divided into three fields and in multiple (3) ownership. On Heritage at Risk Register (2015).
Management_Land_Use_Comments: General cultivation of interior. Some pasture.

Management_Condition_Comments: Part of outer bank on NE destroyed by farmyard works. This area and N part of three ramparts in different ownership to rest where fencing affects site. Affected by open woodland, garden and shrubs also on parts of fort. Access problems. Outside the fort quarrying.
Management_Land_Use_Comments: Woodland, rough grass, farmyard and developments on site.

Management_Condition_Comments: Most of site, apart from the outer N rampart,under Forestry Commission ownership. Scrub clearance and bracken and bramble control in Forestry Commission area undertaken through management agreement since 2004, including removal of conifers. Possible harvesting problems in N part of site.
Management_Land_Use_Comments: Part of N rampart under commercial conifer plantation.

Management_Condition_Comments: Interior severely affected by ploughing and much of the earthworks lost. A management agreement is now in force to revert the cultivated interior to pasture.

Management_Land_Use_Comments: Destroyed by quarrying and mining. Now moorland and heath vegetation. SSSI.

Management_Condition_Comments: Since the 1980's the cultivated interior and fields to the S and N have been managed under permanent pasture and management agreements, with scrub and tree growth clearance.
Management_Land_Use_Comments: The rampart edge to the N and E and outside the fort under long term woodland. History of ploughing but interior and elsewhere now under permanent pasture.

Management_Condition_Comments: Generally upstanding, but fencing located on the W rampart.
Management_Land_Use_Comments: Woodland and scrub with dense planting of mixed wood to S.

Management_Condition_Comments: Ramparts and interior wooded with gradual scrub control by owner during the past decade. A road impinges on the W rampart and ditch.
Management_Land_Use_Comments: Late 20th C site part planted with conifers and colonised by secondary wood. Road impinges on the W side.

Management_Condition_Comments: Repairs were undertaken 1986-7, 1992 by National Trust and stock reduced over the past decade. To a degree latter resulted in increased bracken encroachment.
Management_Land_Use_Comments: Good pasture, but best seen in winter as badly affected by bracken.

Management_Condition_Comments: Open access with some erosion from quad bikes and animals, but defences difficult to interpret.
Indefinite defences, with scarp and traces of ditch. The site is the subject of National Trust management.
Management_Land_Use_Comments: The site was planted with conifers in the first half of the last century but these have now been cleared with subsequent heath, scrub and bracken regeneration. Plantation surrounds the site.

Management_Condition_Comments: Bracken management and aerial spraying have revealed hut platforms.
Management_Land_Use_Comments: Pasture and mature oaks, fine and well preserved, but slopes below tree-covered.

Management_Condition_Comments: Tree cover removed by storm and clearance by 1981, now pasture and well preserved, Some visitor erosion. FC management of regenerating scrub, saplings and bracken.
Management_Land_Use_Comments: Managed grassland. Slopes below tree covered. Possible warrener's lodge platform.

Management_Condition_Comments: Interior taken out of cultivation in the 1990's. Site now in good private management. 15-20 m buffer strip to ramparts in field to the N side. Area of site to the W in separate ownership.
Management_Land_Use_Comments: Tree-covered slopes and part-wooded defences especially on the N, S and W ramparts. Holly scrub and bracken. Grazed areas within wooded areas. Past history of ploughing.

Main_Display_Name: Caer Caradoc, Clun, Shropshire (Caer Caradoc, Chapel Lawn; Gaer Ditches)
Management_Condition_Comments: Well preserved hillfort with some stock erosion, but gorse in interior which has increased in the past 20 years poses management problems. Successful 1995 erosion repairs at W entrance.
Management_Land_Use_Comments: Pasture with gorse scrub in the interior.

Management_Condition_Comments: Popular site for recreation with path erosion on N and S ramparts and deep erosion scar below rock outcrops N of the entrance, but generally on good condition.
Management_Land_Use_Comments: Hill top heath and rough grazing with bare rocky outcrops. SSSI.
Wooded slopes above the River Camlad.

Management_Condition_Comments: Successful earthwork repairs c. 2006. Good management.

Much affected by Calcot Farm, which has destroyed areas to the SW in particular, but also on the E side. Modern field road cuts through the bank where the S and E circuits join. Water tank occupies the highest point.
Affected by development, mountain bikes and general vandalism since 1981. On Heritage at Risk Register (2015).
Management_Land_Use_Comments: The fort is covered by scrub and bracken and regenerative oak coppice.

Management_Condition_Comments: Vehicle erosion in the past, but under good management for decades.

Main_Display_Name: Castle Ring, Gorsty Bank, Shropshire (Gorsty Bank)
Management_Condition_Comments: The site has nearly been levelled. Former management of bracken and gorse scrub ceased and now deterioration in condition.
Management_Land_Use_Comments: Pasture and gorse scrub now covers over nearly three-quarters of the site. Bracken is a problem.

Management_Condition_Comments: The S rampart has been ploughed-down and dispersed.

Main_Display_Name: Castle Hill, Oak Hill, Shropshire (Oak Hill)
Management_Land_Use_Comments: Heather moor and heath with bracken.

Management_Condition_Comments: Good with reductions in stock numbers improving condition.
Pasture and woodland, but some ash tree colonisation and scrub causing problems to be addressed. Motte and bailey castle.
Management_Land_Use_Comments: Pasture, wood and scrub. Motte and bailey castle.

Management_Condition_Comments: Fine example of a univallate fort in good condition. Management plan for trees in operation with public access footpath and interpretation. Post-medieval quarry in W just beyond the inner rampart. Some erosion on N rampart top exposing dry-stone walling. Pasture and part tree-clad on inner ramparts to the N. Windthrow has occurred in the past. Some fencing on ramparts.
Management_Land_Use_Comments: General pasture interior with part tree-clad on inner ramparts to the N. Quarrying.

Management_Condition_Comments: Intensive arable in interior with mature woodland on ramparts has damaged the site. Site unlikely to return to pasture in the foreseeable future.
Management_Land_Use_Comments: Intensive arable in the interior, with mature woodland with scrub understorey on the ramparts. Scrub and woodland in annexe.

Management_Condition_Comments: Nearly lost to quarrying with poor rampart survival as ragged scarp only on the SE. Bell-pits and spoil heaps over existing rampart, in relict interior and surrounds. Quarry taken rest of site to NW.
Management_Land_Use_Comments: Moorland and heath on Brown Clee Hill summit. Quarry, spoil heaps.

Management_Condition_Comments: Part-destroyed and heavily disturbed MOD site with buildings remains, including a roofless 19th century hunting lodge/summerhouse at the highest point, with possibly  one to three others. Rampart tumbled and gone apart from on the N and SE.
Heavily overgrown with commercial forestry problems and defences truncated on the N by a forestry road and bank concealed by upcast. Quarry pits outside the E rampart undated.
Management_Land_Use_Comments: Commercial forestry on a former ancient woodland site and heavily overgrown with young saplings. Forestry road.

Management_Condition_Comments: Good management by Shropshire Wildlife Trust as a nature reserve and well preserved. Some rabbit and visitor erosion.
Management_Land_Use_Comments: Upland pasture with bare rock outcrops. Possible WWII emplacement.

Management_Condition_Comments: Badly affected by caravan site and part wooded with WWII station. Permissive paths throughout site for campers
Management_Land_Use_Comments: Camping and caravan site and part wooded.

Management_Condition_Comments: The site of a possible later signal station of indeterminate recorded date, the site is now under management agreement and pasture. Selected deciduous tree removal occurred in the 1990's and conifers were removed from the SW corner. Scrub and bracken have been controlled over the past decade.
Management_Land_Use_Comments: Pasture with scrub and bracken management. Possible later signal station.

Main_Display_Name: Haughmond Hill Camp, Shropshire (Haughmond Castle; Castle Earthwork)
Management_Condition_Comments: Affected by scrub and trees and Forestry Commission public access site problems. 18th century folly of Haughmond Castle in interior as are remnants of a WWII spigot mortar emplacement, possibly used by the Home Guard. Toposcope and managed tracks with erosion.
Management_Land_Use_Comments: Recreation site with scrub and bracken. Folly and WWII works. Toposcope.

Management_Condition_Comments: Pasture and surviving ramparts generally stable, but E line missing. Affected by development.
Management_Land_Use_Comments: Affected by domestic properties and playing field, but down to permanent pasture.

Management_Condition_Comments: Site much damaged by houses, gardens and quarrying. Golf course in interior and public footpaths over site. Past mineral extraction from prehistoric times on part of site, but golf course has obscured many features.
Management_Land_Use_Comments: Golf course and buildings, scrub and bare rock.

Management_Condition_Comments: Ramparts and entrances mostly well-preserved, but some sheep scrapes on the NE and S. Management prescriptions sought.
Management_Land_Use_Comments: Good pasture. Small ditched enclosure to its SW. The latter is certainly a WWII Home Guard site.

Management_Condition_Comments: Interior under intensive arable cultivation and ramparts tree covered with major scrub, including laurel, problems. This has encouraged burrowing animals which are causing major erosion problems. The site is deteriorating in condition. Small stone quarries in the NW sector. On Heritage at Risk Register (2015).
Management_Land_Use_Comments: Ramparts tree covered with dense scrub, including laurel, and interior cultivated.

Management_Condition_Comments: Good condition but has suffered from scrub and bracken encroachment in the past which poses management problems. Very popular recreation site results in some visitor erosion.
Management_Land_Use_Comments: Interior grazed, as were the banks in the past. SSSI.

Management_Condition_Comments: Wooded Country Park owned by Shropshire Council.
Management_Land_Use_Comments: Very dense woodland, scrub and bracken. Former coniferous plantation. Dense undergrowth with understorey of rododendron.

Management_Condition_Comments: Intensive arable cultivation and ploughing have reduced much of the site to a cropmark. The detritus associated with domestic properties litters part of the site, but site boundaries are generally defined by fences with concrete posts.
Management_Land_Use_Comments: Most of the site is down to intensive arable, but some of the earthwork is within the curtilage of domestic properties.

Management_Condition_Comments: Part-wooded. Forestry Commission access road cuts along main ditch slicing off the front edge of the counterscarp of the outer rampart. Paths and boundary bank confuse matters. Some visitor erosion as open access.
Management_Land_Use_Comments: Young trees, scrub and bracken dominate the site. Substantial forestry road. SSSI.

Management_Condition_Comments: Formerly an ancient woodland site, planted with conifers in 20th century, but vegetation clearance in  2010 as part of a butterfly conservation project has now exposed the hillfort. Some saplings and mature conifers remain.
Management_Land_Use_Comments: Upland pasture with some saplings and mature conifers.

Main_Display_Name: Ratlinghope Hill Camp, Shropshire (Ratlinghope Hill; Stitt Hill)
Management_Condition_Comments: Bracken problem and minor disturbance, but generally improving in stability.
Paert-destroyed and very badly affected by development as a farmhouse and ancillary farm buildings and yards are located within the enclosure. Banks ploughed-down and dispersed.
Management_Land_Use_Comments: Farm located in the interior and site cultivated.

Management_Condition_Comments: Excavation trenches of 1930's and 1960's still open and causing problems.
Management_Land_Use_Comments: Interior under pasture with ramparts generally under deciduous trees and scrub, especially at NE end with conifers. Open trenches.

Management_Condition_Comments: The site is farmed and generally in good condition, although a tractor track crosses the ramparts in the large enclosure, early quarrying has taken place in the smaller and the entrances have been mutilated.
Management_Land_Use_Comments: Unimproved, poorly drained, pasture with scrub on the NW and NE slopes. Early quarrying.

Main_Display_Name: The Burgs, Shropshire (The Buries; Bayston Hill)
Management_Condition_Comments: Much affected by housing development up to the 1970' and as a result the complex banks of the S/SW corner have either been destroyed or are situated within domestic curtilages. Section 17 agreement has put in place a scrub clearance programme.  On Heritage at Risk Register (2015).
Management_Land_Use_Comments: Pasture, wood and scrub with housing encroachment.

Main_Display_Name: The Ditches, Mogg Forest, Shropshire (Larden Ditches; Mogg Ditches; The Rings; Wynbury Castle; Larden Castle)
Management_Condition_Comments: Hillwash has reduced the inner bank to a scarp on the NW and the middle and inner ramparts have been damaged near the SW entrance, itself damaged by a forestry track, but generally ramparts well-preserved. Some windblow problems.
Management_Land_Use_Comments: Conifers and old coppice; W part in deciduous woodland. Part-ploughed in the interior.

Management_Condition_Comments: Some stock erosion at E end and NW corner of N rampart.
The site is in general good condition.
Vestiges remain of the site with some recreation erosion effects.

Although damaged by WWII searchlight battery and warning beacon construction and the 1973 television transmitter between the two enclosures to the NW, the site is large enough to show its salient features well. Bracken, scrub and tree growth.
Management_Land_Use_Comments: Essentially moorland with rock outcrops and modern built features. SSSI.

Management_Condition_Comments: Apart from two small sections between the two large quarries that bite into the fort, the S side has been lost to quarrying for dolorite. The excavated main SE entrance still has the remains of O'Neil's trench exposed. A CAA and Met Office radar station, constructed in the latter 20th century occupies part of the interior.
Management_Land_Use_Comments: A CAA and Met Office radar station, constructed in the latter 20th century occupies part of the interior. Trenches. Quarries.

Main_Display_Name: Wall Camp, Kynnersley, Shropshire (The Wall; Kinnersley Wall)
Management_Condition_Comments: Damaged in the past with Wall Farm located in centre of the fort, with associated buildings, fences, roads etc. Now in good management.
Management_Land_Use_Comments: Under permanent pasture, with some scrub and trees dotted about the site. Wall farm.

Management_Condition_Comments: Stock erosion on inner W rampart and open scrub on ramparts.
Some quarrying has occurred across the bank in the SW and within the interior, but otherwise a well-preserved bank and ditch.

Main_Display_Name: Bussock Camp, West Berkshire (Bussock Wood Camp)
Management_Condition_Comments: The ramparts are now denuded and damage has occurred probably through gravel quarrying.  The banks were said to have stood at 3.6m in the N and 6.1m high in the W Cotton (1962: 45)
Management_Land_Use_Comments: Lies within the grounds of a 20th century country house
Grassland with semi-improved grassland in the northern sector

Management_Condition_Comments: Survives as a bank lying in Ramsbury Wood in the N and E but ploughed out in the S-W and only visible on aerial photographs
E side of fort part destroyed by WWII airfield and interior ploughed with overgrown wooded ramparts. On Heritage at Risk Register (2015).
Management_Land_Use_Comments: Cultivated interior with wooded and overgrown ramparts. WWII airfield.

Management_Condition_Comments: Suffers damage from unauthorised vehicles and heathland fires. On Heritage at Risk Register (2015).
Management_Land_Use_Comments: Aerial imagery suggests the land is under scrub.

Management_Condition_Comments: Upstanding but almost destroyed. Best preserved in the N where it lies in unploughed grassland.
Some erosion has occurred and possible damage to interior features from conifer plantation
Management_Land_Use_Comments: Until 1994 the site was covered by conifer plantation.  Some trees remain on the ramparts with grass and heathland in the interior. Plateau gravels overlying sand of the Barton Beds

Management_Condition_Comments: Modern quarrying and agriculture have destroyed the southern and eastern extents of the site.
Management_Land_Use_Comments: Appears from satellite imagery to be unimproved grazing. Land owned by the National Trust, No. 20443

Management_Condition_Comments: The site is visible as a cropmark on aerial photographs and earthwork on lidar in Great Barrock Wood.  Principle threat is from ploughing (Heritage at Risk Register 2013)
Management_Land_Use_Comments: Lies in an area of arable fields. A conifer plantation is present on the western edge.

Main_Display_Name: Humbledon Hill, Tyne and Wear (Homeldon; Hamdon; Hamylden; Hamildon; Humbledon Bank)
Management_Condition_Comments: Sub-surface ditches with a surviving bank
Management_Land_Use_Comments: Housing Estate with rough grassland in the W

Management_Condition_Comments: Upstanding but the surrounding drystone rampart has tumbled with a recorded spread of up to 17m in places.
The rampart is now lost in the N and E
Slate quarrying has removed the SW corner of the rampart
Management_Land_Use_Comments: The land is now owned by the National Trust, HER Ref. 20125.
Earthworks survive well in woodland but are cut into by an old quarry on its NE side.

Management_Condition_Comments: Survives as rock-cut ditches and platforms
Management_Land_Use_Comments: Land owned by the National Trust Ref No 27504

Management_Condition_Comments: A measured survey by Green Lane Archaeology in 2012 recorded considerable differences in the state of erosion across the hillfort with heavy erosion on the western side which is common land. It is overgrown in the E but with only minor erosion. Erosion has been caused almost entirely by footfall and the use of motorbikes on the site.  A trig point towards the SW of the site has been placed on top of an artificial earthwork forming part of the monument, and erosion is particularly severe in this area. Images of snowboarding on the ramparts on GE imagery
Management_Land_Use_Comments: The fort is divided NS by the parish boundary which is marked by a wall. It is grazed in the W, but bracken and gorse have been allowed to grow in the east. The western side is common land in private ownership
A well-preserved enclosure sited on a bare outcrop with patches of heather

Management_Condition_Comments: It is uncertain if the hill was ever enclosed or if the defences have been destroyed.
Management_Land_Use_Comments: The site is currently on land owned by a field study centre and used for recreational purposes

Management_Condition_Comments: Deep ploughing associated with the planting of the woodland has caused damage across the interior and the bank in the W, reducing it to an outward facing scarp up to 3 m high, with only minimal traces of a counter scarp towards the southern end.
Management_Land_Use_Comments: Planted with mixed conifers and deciduous trees

Management_Condition_Comments: The bank is now low and the ditch partially infilled

The site has been deep ploughed since the 1940's and it is uncertain if any internal features survive (Bewley 1992, 37-8). Coastal erosion has also resulted in subsidence in the NW and is at risk of further erosion
It currently lies within unmanaged woodland and is included in the Heritage at Risk Register 2015 as vulnerable from scrub and tree growth

Management_Land_Use_Comments: The site is owned by the National Trust Ref No; 20303

Management_Condition_Comments: The central part of the rampart in the east has eroded downslope
The monument survives in reasonably good condition but is overgrown

Main_Display_Name: Kemp's Walk, Meikle Larbrax, Dumfries & Galloway (Kemp's Wark)
Management_Condition_Comments: While in relatively good condition, the outer ramparts have been damaged by cultivation, and there are traces of rig crossing the interior
Management_Land_Use_Comments: Bracken clothes the sides of the promontory and there are scattered gorse bushes on the ramparts

Main_Display_Name: Dunskey Golf Course, Dumfries & Galloway (Portpatrick Post Office Radio Station; Fort Cottage)

Management_Condition_Comments: Poor condition. The site has been ploughed and damage has occurred.
Management_Land_Use_Comments: Ploughed in the past, its current use is unknown but aerial coverage appears to show grassland, possibly grazed.

Management_Condition_Comments: In some places the wall has completely disappeared.
Little of the wall remains visible on the very summit.

Main_Display_Name: Fort Point, Larbrax Moor, Dumfries & Galloway (Salt Pans Bay, Galdenoch)
Cassington Ring, Oxfordshire (Cassington Mill Big Ring)

Management_Condition_Comments: Site is cut by a road NE to SW. Outer rampart ploughed away to north and west. South and East damaged by golf course greens. Inner rampart visible for most of its circuit.

Management_Land_Use_Comments: Shown as upstanding multivallate on aerial photos of 1947, has since been flattened by ploughing except for small section of rampart under scrub on NE side.
Small enclosure is extant earthwork (National Trust and pasture), large enclosure is ploughed out and visible as a cropmark.

Extensively mutilated by gravel digging and tree-felling, especially to the N and W. Along the SE side, the counter-scarp of the ditch has been destroyed by the construction of a woodland boundary bank. The N part of the earthwork, much reduced and masked by rhododendron bushes. Tree and brush cover over most of the site.
Badly damaged by ploughing and tree cover, some quarrying of the southern ramparts, best preserved run of rampart is in the NW. Interior and much of the rampart under arable.

Ramparts survive around north-western and south-western quadrants as lynchets on the top of the slope. Complicated to north and west by (later) field terraces. Eastern side of site ploughed down, some tree cover on south and north-east.

Main_Display_Name: Little Coxwell Camp, Oxfordshire (Lower Coxwell Camp; Onetree Hill)
Management_Land_Use_Comments: Single bank and ditch best preserved at north and west, south eastern area destroyed by the building of a house. Stretches of rampart ploughed away.
Inner rampart eroded but ditch and counterscarp bank well preserved, mostly pasture, some tree cover in interior and on N and NE ramparts

Upstanding ramparts for the whole circuit although outer ramparts on the E side have gone, has been ploughed in the interior but now pasture, woodland along the W ramparts, patches of scrub in other areas, rampart damage due to animals

Inner rampart is upstanding earthwork for most of the circuit, within National Trust woodland, some damage due to trees and tracks, possible counterscarp bank is much eroded but still visible in places
Rampart survives as a low bank, ditch visible on aerial photographs as are some internal features. Under arable cultivation and pasture.
Preservation is good for rampart, ditch, counterscarp and western entrance. Interior has been ploughed in the past, now National Trust, sheep grazing. SSSI.

Upstanding bank for complete circuit with stonework eroding, some signs of a filled in ditch. Rampart is tree covered, interior has been ploughed in the past as are the fields around the site, interior now pastur.

Upstanding for most of the circuit but in poor condition, bivallate with ditches, outer bank slight, inner bank survives in places, some small-scale quarry damage on the W. Whole site covered with trees and scrub.
